<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-04-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-04-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="436" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d436">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 811.304M28/72.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Minister</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-02">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 2, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>In concluding his message read in the opening of the Congress yesterday
                            afternoon, President Gómez said: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>I do not wish to conclude this message without recording an event
                                    that has demonstrated to the entire world the close ties of
                                    affection which bind us to <pb facs="0425" n="309" xml:id="pg_309"/> American people. I refer to the imposing
                                    obsequies and the manifestation of mourning accorded to the
                                    remains of the sailors found in the wreck of the battleship <hi rend="italic">Maine</hi>, and the removal of the wreck from
                                    our jurisdictional waters. Our Government and the American
                                    Government were associated in this act and, inspired by a common
                                    sentiment, fulfilled a pious duty.</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Beaupré</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>